        understand: "Explain why a single nucleotide insertion typically causes more damage to a protein than a single nucleotide substitution. Your answer must reference the effect of each on the reading frame and the downstream amino acid sequence.",
        apply:      "The wild-type sequence of a gene at codons 4–7 is: AAA-CGU-GAC-UGG (Lys-Arg-Asp-Trp). Determine the amino acid sequence if: (a) position 11 (first base of GAC) is deleted; (b) codon 6 changes from GAC to GAG; (c) codon 7 changes from UGG to UGA. For each, classify the mutation type and state whether the protein is likely to be functional.",
        analyze:    "Three bacteria are plated on the Ames test: compound W gives 11 revertants (background 12); compound X gives 450 revertants with S9 and 13 without S9; compound Y gives 310 revertants without S9 and 320 with S9. (a) Classify each compound. (b) For compound X, explain what the S9 fraction does and what type of compound X is. (c) State what further experiments would determine whether compound X is an animal carcinogen.",
        evaluate:   "Evaluate the following claim: 'The SOS response in bacteria is a high-fidelity DNA repair pathway that corrects mutations caused by DNA damage.' Identify all errors in this statement, explain what the SOS response actually does, specify which polymerases are involved and why they are inaccurate, and state the biological purpose this inaccuracy serves.",
        create:     "Propose a modified Ames test protocol to specifically detect compounds that cause frameshift mutations (insertions or deletions) rather than base substitutions. Include: (a) the type of Salmonella strain you would engineer (specify what his mutation you would use and why); (b) how you would confirm that revertants are genuine frameshifts and not base substitution revertants; (c) a positive control compound and a negative control compound; (d) how you would incorporate S9 to detect pro-frameshift mutagens."
